04744nam a22005655i 9780822382690DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19951995ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223826907 a10.1515/97808223826902doi  a(DE-B1597)554582  a(OCoLC)1136297204  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1992.6b.F44 1995 7aSOC0520002bisacsh1 aFeuer, Jane, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeeing Through the Eighties :bTelevision and Reaganism /cJane Feuer; Lynn Spigel. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1995] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (180 p.) :b87 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aConsole-ing passions: television and cultural power00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Relationship between Politics and Television in the Reagan Era -- t1 The Made-for-TV "Trauma Drama": Neoconservative Nightmare or Radical Critique? -- t2 The Yuppie Spectator -- t3 Yuppie Envy and Yuppie Guilt: L.A. Law and thirtysomething -- t4 Art Discourse in 1980s Television: Modernism as Postmodernism -- t5 Serial Form, Melodrama, and Reaganite Ideology in Eighties TV -- t6 The Reception of Dynasty -- tAfterword: Overturning the Reagan Era -- tAppendix A: Trauma Dramas -- tAppendix B: Yuppie Programs -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1980s saw the rise of Ronald Reagan and the New Right in American politics, the popularity of programs such as thirtysomething and Dynasty on network television, and the increasingly widespread use of VCRs, cable TV, and remote control in American living rooms. In Seeing Through the Eighties, Jane Feuer critically examines this most aesthetically complex and politically significant period in the history of American television in the context of the prevailing conservative ideological climate. With wit, humor, and an undisguised appreciation of TV, she demonstrates the richness of this often-slighted medium as a source of significance for cultural criticism and delivers a compelling decade-defining analysis of our most recent past.With a cast of characters including Michael, Hope, Elliot, Nancy, Melissa, and Gary; Alexis, Krystle, Blake, and all the other Carringtons; not to mention Maddie and David; even Crockett and Tubbs, Feuer smoothly blends close readings of well-known programs and analysis of television's commercial apparatus with a thorough-going theoretical perspective engaged with the work of Baudrillard, Fiske, and others. Her comparative look at Yuppie TV, Prime Time Soaps, and made-for-TV-movie Trauma Dramas reveals the contradictions and tensions at work in much prime-time programming and in the frustrations of the American popular consciousness. Seeing Through the Eighties also addresses the increased commodification of both the producers and consumers of television as a result of technological innovations and the introduction of new marketing techniques. Claiming a close relationship between television and the cultures that create and view it, Jane Feuer sees the eighties through televison while seeing through television in every sense of the word.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aTelevision and politicszUnited States. 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTelevision viewerszUnited StatesxPsychology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aSpigel, Lynn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382690zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382690423Coveruhttps:/